                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      US antitrust regulator sues Intel
                            
	Washington, Dec. 16 (Reuters): The US government filed a suit against Intel Corp on Wednesday, accusing the chip giant of illegally using its market dominance to stifle competition for a decade.        
	The Federal Trade Commission one of the two US agencies that enforce antitrust law  said Intel was trying to shut its competitors out of the market.        
	Shares of Intel fell 2 per cent on the news, while shares of chip competitors such as Advanced Micro Devices Inc and Nvidia Corp rose around 6 per cent.        
	Intel has engaged in a deliberate campaign to hamstring competitive threats to its monopoly, said Richard Feinstein, director of the FTCs bureau of competition.        
	Its been running roughshod over the principles of fair play and the laws protecting competition on the merits. Intel makes 80 per cent of the worlds central processing units, the brains of personal computers.        
	Microsoft relief        
	The European Union has settled its decade-long antitrust dispute with US software giant Microsoft, paving the way for consumers to have a wider choice of web browsers.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           
